Currently, this is properly parsed by Desktop and GWT, which basically use the same mechanism for internal and classpath files:

```
  com.badlogic.gdx.graphics.g2d.BitmapFont: { 
    default: { file: { com/badlogic/gdx/utils/arial-15.fnt }
  }
```

However, this fails on Android. It would be nice if you could reference fonts located at classpath (for example - provided by external libraries), so you wouldn't have to include your own font files. Very useful for prototyping.

#### Issue details

In the default shader, we declare directional light like that:

```
struct DirectionalLight
{
    vec3 color;
    vec3 direction;
};
uniform DirectionalLight u_dirLights[numDirectionalLights];
```

In the DefaultShader.java, we access it by `u_dirLights[0].color` .

Here the amazing compilation:
- if `numDirectionalLights > 1` : No problem!
- if `numDirectionalLights == 1` : Oh my g*\* `u_dirLights[0].color` is inexistant (location = -1).
#### WHY ??

Because if there is only one element in the array (numDirectionalLights == 1),
`uniform DirectionalLight u_dirLights[numDirectionalLights];` becomes `uniform DirectionalLight u_dirLights`. You must use `u_dirLights.color` and not `u_dirLights[0].color` to access this element.

Sadly DefaultShader doesn't handle this exception, so you can't have only one directional light.

